    ðŸ”¹ `-f charmap`  --> ðŸ—ºï¸ Use `charmap` for encoding. If this option is not provided, `iconv` will be used to convert the character set to UTF-8.
    ðŸ”¹ `-i inputfile` --> ðŸ“¥ Specifies the input locale definition file. If this option is not given, it reads from `stdin`.

ðŸ›  **Examples:**

    $ localedef -c -f UTF-8 -i fa_IR fa_IR.UTF-8

    ðŸ”¹ Creates the `fa_IR.UTF-8` locale from the `fa_IR` file using the `UTF-8` encoding. Displays warnings but continues locale creation.

    $ localedef -f ISO-8859-1 -i en_US en_US.ISO-8859-1

    ðŸ”¹ Creates the `en_US.ISO-8859-1` locale from the `en_US` file using the `ISO-8859-1` encoding.

âœ… **Simple Example:**

